```
import React, { useState } from "react";

function SelectComponent() {
  const [selectedOption, setSelectedOption] = useState("");

  const handleOptionChange = (event) => {
    setSelectedOption(event.target.value);
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <select onChange={handleOptionChange} value={selectedOption}>
        <option value="">Select an option</option>
        <option value="option1">Option 1</option>
        <option value="option2">Option 2</option>
        <option value="option3">Option 3</option>
      </select>
    </div>
  );
}

function useStateWebhook(initialValue) {
  const [value, setValue] = useState(initialValue);

  return [value, (newValue) => setValue(newValue)];
}

function App() {
  const [selectedOption, setSelectedOption] = useStateWebhook("");

  return (
    <div>
      <h3>Selected Option: {selectedOption}</h3>
      <SelectComponent setSelectedOption={setSelectedOption} />
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```

In this example, we first define a `SelectComponent` that includes a `useState` hook to manage the selected option. We then define a `useStateWebhook` function that takes an initial value and returns an array containing the current value and a setter function to update the value. 

In the `App` component, we use the `useStateWebhook` function to manage the selected option state, and pass the `setSelectedOption` function as a prop to the `SelectComponent`. When the user selects an option, the `setSelectedOption` function is called and updates the selected option state. The updated selected option value is then displayed on the page.

