1. Use CSS media queries to define a breakpoint for devices with a maximum width of 640px. 
``` css
@media only screen and (max-width: 640px) {
  /* styles for devices less than 640px wide */
}
```

2. Use relative units like percentages, ems, or rems for font sizes, margins, and paddings. This ensures that elements will adjust their size relative to the screen size. 
``` css 
body {
    font-size: 16px;
}

@media only screen and (max-width: 640px) {
  body {
     font-size: 14px;
  }
}
```

3. Ensure that the layout works well on small screens by using a responsive grid system, which will adjust the column widths depending on the screen size. For example, you can use Bootstrap's grid system:

``` html
<div class="container-fluid">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-4">Column 1</div>
    <div class="col-sm-4">Column 2</div>
    <div class="col-sm-4">Column 3</div>
  </div>
</div>
```

In this example, each column will take up 4 out of 12 units on the grid on small screens, evenly distributing the columns across the screen.

4. Ensure that images are optimized for smaller screens. This can be done by using small file sizes, and using CSS to adjust the image size or display as necessary.

